   while (n > 0) { x = n % 2;
        n /= 2;
        s += x;   // but note: this builds the binary in reverse order (LSB first) but then we traverse the string from index0 to end?

The original code only checks the fractional part (the distance to the floor). So it would not count 3.999? But 3.999 is very close to 4, which is an integer. So the original code might have a flaw? Looking at the original Java code: it does:

   double sq = Math.sqrt(dist);
   answer += (Math.abs(sq - Math.floor(sq)) < 0.001 ? 1 : 0);

This only checks the fractional part. But 3.999: 
   sq = 3.999, floor(sq)=3, so the fractional part is 0.999, which is not <0.001 -> not counted. But 3.999 is 4-0.001, which is very close to 4. So we should count it. Therefore, the original code might be incorrect for such cases. However, note that the squared distance is an integer.
